# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inductive-sensing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In electromagnetism, an **eddy current** (also called **Foucault's current**) is a loop of electric current induced within conductors by a changing magnetic field in the conductor according to Faraday's law of induction or by the relative motion of a conductor in a magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents flow in closed loops within conductors, in planes perpendicular to the magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] They can be induced within nearby stationary conductors by a time-varying magnetic field created by an AC electromagnet or transformer, for example, or by relative motion between a magnet and a nearby conductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The magnitude of the current in a given loop is proportional to the strength of the magnetic field, the area of the loop, and the rate of change of flux, and inversely proportional to the resistivity of the material.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] When graphed, these circular currents within a piece of metal look vaguely like eddies or whirlpools in a liquid.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] By Lenz's law, an eddy current creates a magnetic field that opposes the change in the magnetic field that created it, and thus eddy currents react back on the source of the magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] For example, a nearby conductive surface will exert a drag force on a moving magnet that opposes its motion, due to eddy currents induced in the surface by the moving magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This effect is employed in eddy current brakes which are used to stop rotating power tools quickly when they are turned off.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The current flowing through the resistance of the conductor also dissipates energy as heat in the material.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Thus eddy currents are a cause of energy loss in alternating current (AC) inductors, transformers, electric motors and generators, and other AC machinery, requiring special construction such as laminated magnetic cores or ferrite cores to minimize them.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents are also used to heat objects in induction heating furnaces and equipment, and to detect cracks and flaws in metal parts using eddy-current testing instruments.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The term *eddy current* comes from analogous currents seen in water in fluid dynamics, causing localised areas of turbulence known as *eddies* giving rise to persistent vortices.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Somewhat analogously, eddy currents can take time to build up and can persist for very long times in conductors due to their inductance.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The first person to observe eddy currents was François Arago (1786–1853).
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In 1824 he observed what has been called rotatory magnetism, and that most conductive bodies could be magnetized; these discoveries were completed and explained by Michael Faraday (1791–1867).
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In 1834, Emil Lenz stated Lenz's law, which says that the direction of induced current flow in an object will be such that its magnetic field will oppose the change of magnetic flux that caused the current flow.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents produce a secondary field that cancels a part of the external field and causes some of the external flux to avoid the conductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] French physicist Léon Foucault (1819–1868) is credited with having discovered eddy currents.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In September 1855, he discovered that the force required for the rotation of a copper disc becomes greater when it is made to rotate with its rim between the poles of a magnet, the disc at the same time becoming heated by the eddy current induced in the metal.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The first use of eddy current for non-destructive testing occurred in 1879 when David E.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Hughes used the principles to conduct metallurgical sorting tests.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] A magnet induces circular electric currents in a metal sheet moving through its magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The accompanying diagram shows a metal sheet C moving to the right with velocity ${\vec {v}}$ under a stationary magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The magnetic field ${\vec {B}}$ (in green arrows) from the magnet's north pole N passes down through the metal sheet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since the metal is moving, the magnetic flux through a given area of the sheet is changing.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In particular, the part of the sheet moving toward the edge of the magnet (the left side) experiences an increase in magnetic flux density ${\frac {dB}{dt}}>0$ .
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This change in magnetic flux, in turn, induces a circular electromotive force (emf) in the sheet, in accordance with Faraday's law of induction, exerting a force on the electrons in the sheet, causing a counterclockwise circular current I in the sheet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Similarly, the part of the sheet moving away from the edge of the magnet (the right side) experiences a decrease in magnetic flux density ${\frac {dB}{dt}}<0$ , inducing a second eddy current, this time in a clockwise direction.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since the electrons have a negative charge, they move in the opposite direction to the conventional current shown by the arrows.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since the charge q of the electrons is negative, by the right-hand rule the force is to the right, looking in the direction of motion of the sheet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] So there is a flow of electrons toward the viewer under the magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This divides into two parts, flowing right and left around the magnet outside the magnetic field back to the far side of the magnet in two circular eddies.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since the electrons have a negative charge, the direction of conventional current arrows I shown is in the opposite direction, toward the left under the magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The electrons collide with the metal lattice atoms, exerting a drag force on the sheet proportional to its velocity.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The kinetic energy used to overcome this drag is dissipated as heat by the currents flowing through the metal, so the metal gets warm under the magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] As described by Ampère's circuital law, each of the circular currents in the sheet induces its own magnetic field (marked in blue arrows in the diagram).
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Another way to understand the drag is to observe that in accordance with Lenz's law, the induced electromotive force must oppose the change in magnetic flux through the sheet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] At the leading edge of the magnet (left side), the anti-clockwise current creates a magnetic field pointing up (as can be shown using the right hand rule), opposing the magnet's field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This causes a repulsive force to develop between the sheet and the leading edge of the magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In contrast, at the trailing edge (right side), the clockwise current causes a magnetic field pointed down, in the same direction as the magnet's field, resulting in an attractive force between the sheet and the trailing edge of the magnet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In both cases, the resulting force is not in the direction of motion of the sheet.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents in conductors of non-zero resistivity generate heat as well as electromagnetic forces.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The heat can be used for induction heating.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The electromagnetic forces can be used for levitation, creating movement, or to give a strong braking effect.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents can also have undesirable effects, for instance power loss in transformers.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In this application, they are minimized with thin plates, by lamination of conductors or other details of conductor shape.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Self-induced eddy currents are responsible for the skin effect in conductors.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The latter can be used for non-destructive testing of materials for geometry features, like micro-cracks.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] A similar effect is the proximity effect, which is caused by externally induced eddy currents.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] An object or part of an object experiences steady field intensity and direction where there is still relative motion of the field and the object (for example in the center of the field in the diagram), or unsteady fields where the currents cannot circulate due to the geometry of the conductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In these situations charges collect on or within the object and these charges then produce static electric potentials that oppose any further current.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Currents may be initially associated with the creation of static potentials, but these may be transitory and small.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents generate resistive losses that transform some forms of energy, such as kinetic energy, into heat.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This Joule heating reduces efficiency of iron-core transformers and electric motors and other devices that use changing magnetic fields.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents are minimized in these devices by selecting magnetic core materials that have low electrical conductivity (e.g., ferrites or iron powder mixed with resin) or by using thin sheets of magnetic material, known as laminations.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Electrons cannot cross the insulating gap between the laminations and so are unable to circulate on wide arcs.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Charges gather at the lamination boundaries, in a process analogous to the Hall effect, producing electric fields that oppose any further accumulation of charge and hence suppressing the eddy currents.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The shorter the distance between adjacent laminations (i.e., the greater the number of laminations per unit area, perpendicular to the applied field), the greater the suppression of eddy currents.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The conversion of input energy to heat is not always undesirable, however, as there are some practical applications.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] One is in the brakes of some trains known as eddy current brakes.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] During braking, the metal wheels are exposed to a magnetic field from an electromagnet, generating eddy currents in the wheels.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This eddy current is formed by the movement of the wheels.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] So, by Lenz's law, the magnetic field formed by the eddy current will oppose its cause.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Thus the wheel will face a force opposing the initial movement of the wheel.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The faster the wheels are spinning, the stronger the effect, meaning that as the train slows the braking force is reduced, producing a smooth stopping motion.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Induction heating makes use of eddy currents to provide heating of metal objects.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This equation is valid only under the so-called quasi-static conditions, where the frequency of magnetisation does not result in the skin effect; that is, the electromagnetic wave fully penetrates the material.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In very fast-changing fields, the magnetic field does not penetrate completely into the interior of the material.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This *skin effect* renders the above equation invalid.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] However, in any case increased frequency of the same value of field will always increase eddy currents, even with non-uniform field penetration.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] By definition, **B** = *μ*0(**H** + **M**), where **M** is the magnetization of the material and *μ*0 is the vacuum permeability.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy current brakes use the drag force created by eddy currents as a brake to slow or stop moving objects.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since there is no contact with a brake shoe or drum, there is no mechanical wear.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] However, an eddy current brake cannot provide a "holding" torque and so may be used in combination with mechanical brakes, for example, on overhead cranes.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Another application is on some roller coasters, where heavy copper plates extending from the car are moved between pairs of very strong permanent magnets.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Electrical resistance within the plates causes a dragging effect analogous to friction, which dissipates the kinetic energy of the car.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The same technique is used in electromagnetic brakes in railroad cars and to quickly stop the blades in power tools such as circular saws.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Using electromagnets, as opposed to permanent magnets, the strength of the magnetic field can be adjusted and so the magnitude of braking effect changed.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In a varying magnetic field, the induced currents exhibit diamagnetic-like repulsion effects.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] A conductive object will experience a repulsion force.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This can lift objects against gravity, though with continual power input to replace the energy dissipated by the eddy currents.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] An example application is separation of aluminum cans from other metals in an eddy current separator.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Ferrous metals cling to the magnet, and aluminum (and other non-ferrous conductors) are forced away from the magnet; this can separate a waste stream into ferrous and non-ferrous scrap metal.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] With a very strong handheld magnet, such as those made from neodymium, one can easily observe a very similar effect by rapidly sweeping the magnet over a coin with only a small separation.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Depending on the strength of the magnet, identity of the coin, and separation between the magnet and coin, one may induce the coin to be pushed slightly ahead of the magnet – even if the coin contains no magnetic elements, such as the US penny.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Another example involves dropping a strong magnet down a tube of copper – the magnet falls at a dramatically slow pace.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In a perfect conductor with no resistance, surface eddy currents exactly cancel the field inside the conductor, so no magnetic field penetrates the conductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Since no energy is lost in resistance, eddy currents created when a magnet is brought near the conductor persist even after the magnet is stationary, and can exactly balance the force of gravity, allowing magnetic levitation.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Superconductors also exhibit a separate inherently quantum mechanical phenomenon called the Meissner effect in which any magnetic field lines present in the material when it becomes superconducting are expelled, thus the magnetic field in a superconductor is always zero.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Using electromagnets with electronic switching comparable to electronic speed control it is possible to generate electromagnetic fields moving in an arbitrary direction.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] As described in the section above about eddy current brakes, a non-ferromagnetic conductor surface tends to rest within this moving field.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] When however this field is moving, a vehicle can be levitated and propelled.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This is comparable to a maglev but is not bound to a rail.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In some coin-operated vending machines, eddy currents are used to detect counterfeit coins, or slugs.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The coin rolls past a stationary magnet, and eddy currents slow its speed.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] The strength of the eddy currents, and thus the retardation, depends on the conductivity of the coin's metal.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Slugs are slowed to a different degree than genuine coins, and this is used to send them into the rejection slot.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents are used in certain types of proximity sensors to observe the vibration and position of rotating shafts within their bearings.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This technology was originally pioneered in the 1930s by researchers at General Electric using vacuum tube circuitry.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] In the late 1950s, solid-state versions were developed by Donald E.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] These sensors are extremely sensitive to very small displacements making them well suited to observe the minute vibrations (on the order of a tenth of a millimeter, or several thousandths of an inch) in modern turbomachinery.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] A typical proximity sensor used for vibration monitoring has a scale factor of 7900 mV/mm (200 mV/mil).
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Widespread use of such sensors in turbomachinery has led to development of industry standards that prescribe their use and application.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Examples of such standards are American Petroleum Institute (API) Standard 670 and ISO 7919.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] A Ferraris acceleration sensor, also called a Ferraris sensor, is a contactless sensor that uses eddy currents to measure relative acceleration.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy current techniques are commonly used for the nondestructive examination (NDE) and condition monitoring of a large variety of metallic structures, including heat exchanger tubes, aircraft fuselage, and aircraft structural components.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Eddy currents are the root cause of the skin effect in conductors carrying alternating current.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] Similarly, in magnetic materials of finite conductivity, eddy currents cause the confinement of the majority of the magnetic fields to only a couple skin depths of the surface of the material.
[src:inductive-sensing/eddy-current] This effect limits the flux linkage in inductors and transformers having magnetic cores.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Inductance is defined as the ratio of the induced voltage to the rate of change of current causing it.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It is a proportionality constant that depends on the geometry of circuit conductors (e.g., cross-section area and length) and the magnetic permeability of the conductor and nearby materials.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] An electronic component designed to add inductance to a circuit is called an inductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It typically consists of a coil or helix of wire.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The term *inductance* was coined by Oliver Heaviside in May 1884, as a convenient way to refer to "coefficient of self-induction".
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It is customary to use the symbol L for inductance, in honour of the physicist Heinrich Lenz.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] In the SI system, the unit of inductance is the henry (H), which is the amount of inductance that causes a voltage of one volt, when the current is changing at a rate of one ampere per second.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The unit is named for Joseph Henry, who discovered inductance independently of Faraday.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Inductance, through its opposition to changes in current, is an indirect manifestation of the concept of electromagnetic mass.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The history of electromagnetic induction, a facet of electromagnetism, began with observations of the ancients: electric charge or static electricity (rubbing silk on amber), electric current (lightning), and magnetic attraction (lodestone).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Understanding the unity of these forces of nature, and the scientific theory of electromagnetism was initiated and achieved during the 19th century.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Electromagnetic induction was first described by Michael Faraday in 1831.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] In Faraday's experiment, he wrapped two wires around opposite sides of an iron ring.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] He expected that, when current started to flow in one wire, a sort of wave would travel through the ring and cause some electrical effect on the opposite side.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Using a galvanometer, he observed a transient current flow in the second coil of wire each time that a battery was connected or disconnected from the first coil.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This current was induced by the change in magnetic flux that occurred when the battery was connected and disconnected.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Faraday found several other manifestations of electromagnetic induction.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] For example, he saw transient currents when he quickly slid a bar magnet in and out of a coil of wires, and he generated a steady (DC) current by rotating a copper disk near the bar magnet with a sliding electrical lead ("Faraday's disk").
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] A current i flowing through a conductor generates a magnetic field around the conductor, which is described by Ampere's circuital law.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The total magnetic flux $\Phi$ through a circuit is equal to the product of the perpendicular component of the magnetic flux density and the area of the surface spanning the current path.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the current varies, the magnetic flux $\Phi$ through the circuit changes.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The negative sign in the equation indicates that the induced voltage is in a direction which opposes the change in current that created it; this is called Lenz's law.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The potential is therefore called a back EMF.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the current is increasing, the voltage is positive at the end of the conductor through which the current enters and negative at the end through which it leaves, tending to reduce the current.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the current is decreasing, the voltage is positive at the end through which the current leaves the conductor, tending to maintain the current.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Thus, inductance is a property of a conductor or circuit, due to its magnetic field, which tends to oppose changes in current through the circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The unit of inductance in the SI system is the henry (H), named after Joseph Henry, which is the amount of inductance that generates a voltage of one volt when the current is changing at a rate of one ampere per second.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] All conductors have some inductance, which may have either desirable or detrimental effects in practical electrical devices.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The inductance of a circuit depends on the geometry of the current path, and on the magnetic permeability of nearby materials; ferromagnetic materials with a higher permeability like iron near a conductor tend to increase the magnetic field and inductance.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] An inductor is an electrical component consisting of a conductor shaped to increase the magnetic flux, to add inductance to a circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Typically it consists of a wire wound into a coil or helix.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] A coiled wire has a higher inductance than a straight wire of the same length, because the magnetic field lines pass through the circuit multiple times, it has multiple flux linkages.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The inductance is proportional to the square of the number of turns in the coil, assuming full flux linkage.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The inductance of a coil can be increased by placing a magnetic core of ferromagnetic material in the hole in the center.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The magnetic field of the coil magnetizes the material of the core, aligning its magnetic domains, and the magnetic field of the core adds to that of the coil, increasing the flux through the coil.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This is called a ferromagnetic core inductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] A magnetic core can increase the inductance of a coil by thousands of times.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If multiple electric circuits are located close to each other, the magnetic field of one can pass through the other; in this case the circuits are said to be *inductively coupled*.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Due to Faraday's law of induction, a change in current in one circuit can cause a change in magnetic flux in another circuit and thus induce a voltage in another circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The concept of inductance can be generalized in this case by defining the mutual inductance $M_{k,\ell }$ of circuit k and circuit $\ell$ as the ratio of voltage induced in circuit $\ell$ to the rate of change of current in circuit k .
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This is the principle behind a *transformer*.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The property describing the effect of one conductor on itself is more precisely called *self-inductance*, and the properties describing the effects of one conductor with changing current on nearby conductors is called *mutual inductance*.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the current through a conductor with inductance is increasing, a voltage $v(t)$ is induced across the conductor with a polarity that opposes the current—in addition to any voltage drop caused by the conductor's resistance.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The charges flowing through the circuit lose potential energy.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The energy from the external circuit required to overcome this "potential hill" is stored in the increased magnetic field around the conductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Therefore, an inductor stores energy in its magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When there is no current, there is no magnetic field and the stored energy is zero.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Neglecting resistive losses, the energy U (measured in joules, in SI) stored by an inductance with a current I through it is equal to the amount of work required to establish the current through the inductance from zero, and therefore the magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Inductance is therefore also proportional to the energy stored in the magnetic field for a given current.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This energy is stored as long as the current remains constant.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the current decreases, the magnetic field decreases, inducing a voltage in the conductor in the opposite direction, negative at the end through which current enters and positive at the end through which it leaves.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This returns stored magnetic energy to the external circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the magnetic field in the inductor approaches the level at which the core saturates, the inductance begins to change with current, and the integral equation must be used.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When a sinusoidal alternating current (AC) is passing through a linear inductance, the induced back-EMF is also sinusoidal.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] where $I_{\text{peak}}$ is the amplitude (peak value) of the sinusoidal current in amperes, $\omega =2\pi f$ is the angular frequency of the alternating current, with f being its frequency in hertz, and L is the inductance.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Inductive reactance is the opposition of an inductor to an alternating current.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It can be seen that inductive reactance of an inductor increases proportionally with frequency f , so an inductor conducts less current for a given applied AC voltage as the frequency increases.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Because the induced voltage is greatest when the current is increasing, the voltage and current waveforms are out of phase; the voltage peaks occur earlier in each cycle than the current peaks.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The phase difference between the current and the induced voltage is $\phi ={\tfrac {1}{2}}\pi$ radians or 90 degrees, showing that in an ideal inductor, *the current lags the voltage by 90°*.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] In the most general case, inductance can be calculated from Maxwell's equations.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Many important cases can be solved using simplifications.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Where high frequency currents are considered, with skin effect, the surface current densities and magnetic field may be obtained by solving the Laplace equation.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Where the conductors are thin wires, self-inductance still depends on the wire radius and the distribution of the current in the wire.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This current distribution is approximately constant (on the surface or in the volume of the wire) for a wire radius much smaller than other length scales.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] As a practical matter, longer wires have more inductance, and thicker wires have less, analogous to their electrical resistance (although the relationships are not linear, and are different in kind from the relationships that length and diameter bear to resistance).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Separating the wire from the other parts of the circuit introduces some unavoidable error in any formulas' results.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] These inductances are often referred to as “partial inductances”, in part to encourage consideration of the other contributions to whole-circuit inductance which are omitted.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] For derivation of the formulas below, see Rosa (1908).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The constant 0.75 is just one parameter value among several; different frequency ranges, different shapes, or extremely long wire lengths require a slightly different constant (see below).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This result is based on the assumption that the radius r is much less than the length $\ell$ , which is the common case for wires and rods.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Disks or thick cylinders have slightly different formulas.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] For example, a single conductor of a lamp cord 10 m long, made of 18 AWG (1.024 mm) wire, would have a low frequency inductance of about 19.67 μH, if stretched out straight.
