[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The inductance matrix, *Lm,n*, thus is symmetric.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] This equation also is a direct consequence of the linearity of Maxwell's equations.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It is helpful to associate changing electric currents with a build-up or decrease of magnetic field energy.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The corresponding energy transfer requires or generates a voltage.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] A mechanical analogy in the *K* = 1 case with magnetic field energy (1/2)*Li*2 is a body with mass *M*, velocity *u* and kinetic energy (1/2)*Mu*2.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The rate of change of velocity (current) multiplied with mass (inductance) requires or generates a force (an electrical voltage).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Mutual inductance occurs when the change in current in one inductor induces a voltage in another nearby inductor.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] It is important as the mechanism by which transformers work, but it can also cause unwanted coupling between conductors in a circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The mutual inductance, $M_{ij}$ , is also a measure of the coupling between two inductors.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The minus sign arises because of the sense the current $i_{2}$ has been defined in the diagram.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] With both currents defined going into the dots the sign of M will be positive (the equation would read with a plus sign instead).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The coupling coefficient is the ratio of the open-circuit actual voltage ratio to the ratio that would be obtained if all the flux coupled from one magnetic circuit to the other.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The coupling coefficient is related to mutual inductance and self inductances in the following way.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The coupling coefficient is a convenient way to specify the relationship between a certain orientation of inductors with arbitrary inductance.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Most authors define the range as $0\leq k<1$ , but some define it as $-1<k<1\,$ .
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Allowing negative values of k captures phase inversions of the coil connections and the direction of the windings.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Mutually coupled inductors can be described by any of the two-port network parameter matrix representations.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] $[\mathbf {y} ]={\frac {1}{s}}{\begin{bmatrix}L_{1}\ M\\M\ L_{2}\end{bmatrix}}^{-1}.$ Where s is the complex frequency variable, $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ are the inductances of the primary and secondary coil, respectively, and M is the mutual inductance between the coils.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Mutual inductance may be applied to multiple inductors simultaneously.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Mutually coupled inductors can equivalently be represented by a T-circuit of inductors as shown.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If the coupling is strong and the inductors are of unequal values then the series inductor on the step-down side may take on a negative value.
