[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Alternatively, two coupled inductors can be modelled using a *π* equivalent circuit with optional ideal transformers at each port.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] While the circuit is more complicated than a T-circuit, it can be generalized to circuits consisting of more than two coupled inductors.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Equivalent circuit elements $L_{\text{s}}$ , $L_{\text{p}}$ have physical meaning, modelling respectively magnetic reluctances of coupling paths and magnetic reluctances of leakage paths.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] For example, electric currents flowing through these elements correspond to coupling and leakage magnetic fluxes.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Ideal transformers normalize all self-inductances to 1 Henry to simplify mathematical formulas.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When a capacitor is connected across one winding of a transformer, making the winding a tuned circuit (resonant circuit) it is called a single-tuned transformer.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When a capacitor is connected across each winding, it is called a double tuned transformer.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] These *resonant transformers* can store oscillating electrical energy similar to a resonant circuit and thus function as a bandpass filter, allowing frequencies near their resonant frequency to pass from the primary to secondary winding, but blocking other frequencies.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The amount of mutual inductance between the two windings, together with the Q factor of the circuit, determine the shape of the frequency response curve.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The advantage of the double tuned transformer is that it can have a wider bandwidth than a simple tuned circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The coupling of double-tuned circuits is described as loose-, critical-, or over-coupled depending on the value of the coupling coefficient k .
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When two tuned circuits are loosely coupled through mutual inductance, the bandwidth is narrow.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] As the amount of mutual inductance increases, the bandwidth continues to grow.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When the mutual inductance is increased beyond the critical coupling, the peak in the frequency response curve splits into two peaks, and as the coupling is increased the two peaks move further apart.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Strongly-coupled self-resonant coils can be used for wireless power transfer between devices in the mid range distances (up to two metres).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Strong coupling is required for a high percentage of power transferred, which results in peak splitting of the frequency response.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] When $\ k=1\ ,$ the inductor is referred to as being 'closely coupled'.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] If in addition, the self-inductances go to infinity, the inductor becomes an 'ideal transformer'.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The power through one inductor is the same as the power through the other.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] These equations neglect any forcing by current sources or voltage sources.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The table below lists formulas for the self-inductance of various simple shapes made of thin cylindrical conductors (wires).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] In general these are only accurate if the wire radius a is much smaller than the dimensions of the shape, and if no ferromagnetic materials are nearby (no magnetic core).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] The notation $\ {\mathcal {O}}(\;\!x\;\!)\$ represents small term(s) that have been dropped to make the formula simpler.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductance] Read the expression $\ ...+{\mathcal {O}}(\;\!x\;\!)\$ as "plus small corrections that vary on the order of $\ x\$ " (see big O notation).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] An **inductive sensor** is an electronic device that operates based on the principle of electromagnetic induction to detect or measure nearby metallic objects.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] An inductor develops a magnetic field when an electric current flows through it; alternatively, a current will flow through a circuit containing an inductor when the magnetic field through it changes.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] This effect can be used to detect metallic objects that interact with a magnetic field.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Non-metallic substances, such as liquids or some kinds of dirt, do not interact with the magnetic field, so an inductive sensor can operate in wet or dirty conditions.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] The inductive sensor is based on Faraday's law of induction.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] by assuming that the induced magnetic field **B** is homogeneous over a section S (the magnetic flux will be expressed $\Phi =B\times S$ ).
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] One form of inductive sensor drives a coil with an oscillator.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] A metallic object approaching the coil will alter the inductance of the coil, producing a change in frequency or a change in the current in the coil.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] These changes can be detected, amplified, compared to a threshold and used to switch an external circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] The coil may have a ferromagnetic core to make the magnetic field more intense and to increase the sensitivity of the device.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] A coil with no ferromagnetic core ("air core") can also be used, especially if the oscillator coil must cover a large area.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Another form of inductive sensor uses one coil to produce a changing magnetic field, and a second coil (or other device) to sense the changes in the magnetic field produced by an object, for example, due to eddy currents induced in a metal object.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Inductive sensors constitute the main element to build a search coil magnetometer, also known as a search coil.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] These are used in many fields of research: magnetotellurics, electromagnetic waves measurement, space magnetometers to investigate electromagnetic waves in space plasma as well as natural electromagnetic waves observations on Earth.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] An inductive proximity sensor is a non-contact electronic proximity sensor.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] It is used for positioning and detection of metal objects.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] The sensing range of an inductive switch is dependent on the type of metal being detected.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Ferrous metals, such as iron and steel, allow for a longer sensing range, while nonferrous metals, such as aluminum and copper, may reduce the sensing range by up to 60 percent.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Since the output of an inductive sensor has two possible states, an inductive sensor is sometimes referred to as an **inductive proximity switch**.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] The sensor consists of an induction loop or detector coil.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Most often this is physically a number of turns of insulated magnet wire wound around a high magnetic permeability core, such as a ferrite ceramic rod or coil form, and the winding may or may not have a feedback tap some number of turns from one end of the total winding.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] It is connected to a capacitance to form a tuned frequency oscillator tank circuit.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] In conjunction with a voltage or current gain device like a transistor or operational amplifier, this forms a tuned frequency oscillator.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] When power is applied, the resulting oscillation is a high frequency alternating electric current in the coil that has a constantly changing magnetic field able to induce eddy currents in proximal (target) conductors.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] The closer the target is and the greater its conductivity (metals are good conductors, for example), the greater the induced eddy currents are and the more effect their resulting opposing magnetic fields have on the magnitude and frequency of the oscillation.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Its magnitude is reduced as the load is increased in a non-magnetic conductor like aluminum because the induced field in the target opposes the source induction field, lowering net inductive impedance and therefore simultaneously tuning the oscillation frequency higher.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] But that magnitude is less affected if the target is a highly magnetically permeable material, like iron, as that high permeability increases the coil inductance, lowering the frequency of oscillation.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Either the magnitude change or the amount of frequency change can serve to define a proximity distance at which the sensors go from on to off, or vice versa.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Common applications of inductive sensors include metal detectors, traffic lights, car washes, and a host of automated industrial processes.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Because the sensor does not require physical contact it is particularly useful for applications where access presents challenges or where dirt is prevalent.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] To control traffic signals at an intersection of roads, an induction loop can be buried in the pavement.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] A circuit connected to the loop can detect the change in its inductance when a vehicle passes over or stops on the loop.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] This can be used to detect vehicles and adjust the timing of traffic signals or provide a turning signal at a busy intersection.
[src:inductive-sensing/inductive-sensor] Inductive sensors, also referred (in this area) as "NMR coils" or "radiofrequency coils", are used to detect the magnetic component of the electromagnetic field associated to the nuclear spin precession in Nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] It is the base of LVDT-type displacement sensors.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] A counterpart to this device that is used for measuring rotary displacement is called a *rotary variable differential transformer* (RVDT).
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] LVDTs are robust, absolute linear position/displacement transducers; inherently frictionless, they have a virtually infinite cycle life when properly used.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] As AC operated LVDTs do not contain any electronics, they can be designed to operate at cryogenic temperatures or up to 1200 °F (650 °C), in harsh environments, and under high vibration and shock levels.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] LVDTs have been widely used in applications such as power turbines, hydraulics, automation, aircraft, satellites, nuclear reactors, and many others.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] These transducers have low hysteresis and excellent repeatability.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The LVDT converts a position or linear displacement from a mechanical reference (zero or null position) into a proportional electrical signal containing phase (for direction) and amplitude (for distance) information.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The LVDT operation does not require an electrical contact between the moving part (probe or core assembly) and the coil assembly, but instead relies on electromagnetic coupling.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The linear variable differential transformer has three solenoidal coils placed end-to-end around a tube.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The center coil is the primary, and the two outer coils are the top and bottom secondaries.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] A cylindrical ferromagnetic core, attached to the object whose position is to be measured, slides along the axis of the tube.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] An alternating current drives the primary and causes a voltage to be induced in each secondary proportional to the length of the core linking to the secondary.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The frequency is usually in the range 1 to 10 kHz.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] As the core moves, the primary's linkage to the two secondary coils changes and causes the induced voltages to change.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The coils are connected so that the output voltage is the difference (hence "differential") between the top secondary voltage and the bottom secondary voltage.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] When the core is in its central position, equidistant between the two secondaries, equal voltages are induced in the two secondary coils, but the two signals cancel, so the output voltage is theoretically zero.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] In practice minor variations in the way in which the primary is coupled to each secondary means that a small voltage is output when the core is central.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] This small residual voltage is due to phase shift and is often called quadrature error.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] It is a nuisance in closed loop control systems as it can result in oscillation about the null point, and may also be unacceptable in simple measurement applications.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] It is a consequence of using synchronous demodulation, with direct subtraction of the secondary voltages at AC.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] Modern systems, particularly those involving safety, require fault detection of the LVDT, and the normal method is to demodulate each secondary separately, using precision half wave or full wave rectifiers, based on op-amps, and compute the difference by subtracting the DC signals.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] There is no quadrature error with this scheme, and the position-dependent difference voltage passes smoothly through zero at the null point.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] If sufficient digital processing capacity is available, it is becoming commonplace to use this to generate the sinusoidal excitation via a DAC and possibly also perform the secondary demodulation via a multiplexed ADC.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] When the core is displaced toward the top, the voltage in top secondary coil increases as the voltage in the bottom decreases.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The resulting output voltage increases from zero.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] This voltage is in phase with the primary voltage.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] When the core moves in the other direction, the output voltage also increases from zero, but its phase is opposite to that of the primary.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The phase of the output voltage determines the direction of the displacement (up or down) and amplitude indicates the amount of displacement.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] A synchronous detector can determine a signed output voltage that relates to the displacement.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The LVDT is designed with long slender coils to make the output voltage essentially linear over displacement up to several inches (several hundred millimetres) long.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The LVDT can be used as an absolute position sensor.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] Even if the power is switched off, on restarting it, the LVDT shows the same measurement, and no positional information is lost.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] Its biggest advantages are repeatability and reproducibility once it is properly configured.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] Also, apart from the uni-axial linear motion of the core, any other movements such as the rotation of the core around the axis will not affect its measurements.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] Because the sliding core does not touch the inside of the tube, it can move without friction, making the LVDT a highly reliable device.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] The absence of any sliding or rotating contacts allows the LVDT to be completely sealed against the environment.
[src:inductive-sensing/linear-variable-differential-transformer] LVDTs are commonly used for position feedback in servomechanisms, and for automated measurement in machine tools and many other industrial and scientific applications.
